    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2222189949" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2222189949" />
    <a title="Dana" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5185762-dana"><img alt="Dana" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1540136971p2/5185762.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2222189949?book_show_action=true">Dec 22, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dana" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dana" href="/user/show/5185762-dana">Dana</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/34643071-seven-days-in-may">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5185762-dana?shelf=kindled">kindled</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5185762-dana?shelf=library">library</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5185762-dana?shelf=read-in-2017">read-in-2017</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5185762-dana?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2222189949" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16794997398264201247">I wanted to like this more than I did. The story of the Lusitania is interesting enough, but it&apos;s all just a backdrop to the soapy stories of the main characters. <a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[Following Isabel, the typist/junior codebreaker in the secretive Room 40, would have been interesting enough if the story was just about what the codebreakers knew about the fate of the Lusitania and what they did. But Izzo had to add in a completely unnecessary story about Isabel&apos;s affair with her former employer as the</span></span>
  <span id="freeText16794997398264201247" style="display:none">I wanted to like this more than I did. The story of the Lusitania is interesting enough, but it's all just a backdrop to the soapy stories of the main characters. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Following Isabel, the typist/junior codebreaker in the secretive Room 40, would have been interesting enough if the story was just about what the codebreakers knew about the fate of the Lusitania and what they did. But Izzo had to add in a completely unnecessary story about Isabel's affair with her former employer as the backstory to how Isabel got into Room 40. All to bring in a fellow former servant who tried to blackmail Isabel with exposing the affair to Isabel's new employers.<br /><br />Same with Sydney - a debutante with a suffragette/political activist streak. She is traveling on the Lusitania with her sister Brooke, and Brooke's fiancé Edward. Defying her snotty and completely unlikeable sister, Sydney trades her first class ticket for one in third class. But no. Sydney and Edward had to fall in love with during the voyage, and Sydney contemplates giving it all up to live with Edward in England. What a way to take a character with unique sensibilities for her time and her turn her into a stereotype. <br /><br />And OF COURSE Brooke would be the only one of the three to die. The story is told from Sydney and Edwards's POV, not Brooke's. Add in the fact that she is so unlikeable, and it's all a dead giveaway (pun intended) how their story would end. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />I just feel like this story didn't need these embellishments. The book could have followed just Isabel or just Sydney without the other "drama" and still have been a good book. But at least this has motivated me to seek out non-fiction books about Room 40 and the Lusitania and read more about this period in time.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16794997398264201247" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


