  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2660177455" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2660177455" />
    <a title="Dana" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5754705-dana"><img alt="Dana" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1588519547p2/5754705.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2660177455?book_show_action=true">Apr 04, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dana" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dana" href="/user/show/5754705-dana">Dana</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2660177455" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3892711525657256546">Seven Days In May was an absolutely stunning historical fiction novel that centered around the final sailing of the Lusitania. This author is a phenomenal writer, and crafted vivid characters that were able to tell varying aspects of the controversy surrounding the German attack on a civilian vessel.<br/><br/>There were three main characters who narrated the novel. They were each given backgrounds that were detailed and acted with such passion it was hard not love all of them! Isabel felt compelled to joi</span>
  <span id="freeText3892711525657256546" style="display:none">Seven Days In May was an absolutely stunning historical fiction novel that centered around the final sailing of the Lusitania. This author is a phenomenal writer, and crafted vivid characters that were able to tell varying aspects of the controversy surrounding the German attack on a civilian vessel.<br /><br />There were three main characters who narrated the novel. They were each given backgrounds that were detailed and acted with such passion it was hard not love all of them! Isabel felt compelled to join the war effort and landed a code breaking job in Room 40, even though it meant facing every stereotype men had of women. She was passionate about saving as many lives as possible and her devotion added the factual background surrounding the information available to the ship’s Captain about a possible enemy attack. Of course, that passion and drive to push the boundaries of what was acceptable for a women to do made her a heroic female protagonist who I admired.<br /><br />Sydney was the real star here. She was a smart socialite who wanted to use her money and influence to encourage a woman’s right to choose and obtain votes for women. In that regard, this book made some serious statements about a woman’s role in the world that were similar to current issues facing females. She landed on the ship to accompany her sister Brooke to travel to England to marry Edward. Brooke wanted to marry someone with a title and Edward needed money to keep his family estate, so automatically, they were both villains who I was primed not to like. The tense dynamic between the sisters brought out so many emotions from these women, and all of it played out very well.<br /><br />All the stories melded together to create a novel that was full of emotion and complete characters, despite the horrific events they all faced. This was so well done that I loved it and really felt for the passengers on this ill fated vessel. I highly recommend this.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3892711525657256546" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


